p: Increased temperature resulted in decreased blood feeding frequency by ALB LI population in [M (32%), L (53%) Fisher’s exact test P < .001] ( Figure 5) while the AEG MI [M (36%), H (27%) Fisher’s exact test P = .09]and AEG MX [M (44%), H (43%) Fisher’s exact test P = .92] populations blood-feeding frequencies were not significantly affected. Ae. aegypti reared at the H temperature regimes had significantly reduced longevity relative to the M temperature regime population (Log-rank [Mantel–Cox] test, Chi-square, df 35.66, 5, P < .001; Figure 6). Ae. albopictus longevity was not affected by temperature (Log-rank [Mantel–Cox] test, P > .001).
